This PR defines an explicit binary product and binary coproduct for functors `F : C ⥤ Type u` for an arbitrary category `C`. This is a generalization of #9704.

Instead of `CategoryTheory.FunctorProd.prod`, I would rather see that as `CategoryTheory.Types.functorProd`.

Sorry for the late reply (I had midterms). I'm coming back to this PR, and I'm wondering what you mean by this. Do you think I should change the namespace to `Types` instead of `FunctorProd`, or are you saying I should move this code to `Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Types.lean`?

`Types.functorProd` and `FunctorToTypes.prod` would be ok. (Presumably `FunctorToTypes.prod` is better because we already have the `FunctorToTypes` namespace; I am sorry for not thinking about this better name in the first place). Then, as I am suggesting below, as this deals with specific shapes of (co)limits for functors to the category of types, the new code should be moved to a new file `Limits.Shapes.FunctorToTypes`, which should also fix the linter issue.
`FunctorToTypes.prod` seems like the best option, thanks.

For future applications of this, I would suggest defining ```def natTransProd {F F₁ F₂ : C ⥤ Type w} (τ₁ : F ⟶ F₁) (τ₂ : F ⟶ F₂) : F ⟶ functorProd F₁ F₂ := sorry``` instead and invoke this `natTransProd` directly in the definition of `binaryProductLimit`.
You should change "simplicial/simplex" to something else.
There is no need for parentheses around `Type u` here. Also, it is important `u` is an arbitrary universe: `Type w` would be better.
As the linter complains, I would suggest moving everything to a new file `Limits.Shapes.FunctorToTypes`, and renaming this definition as `CategoryTheory.FunctorToTypes.prod`.
This one should be renamed `FunctorToTypes.coprod`.

Parentheses are not necessary here, and below:
```suggestion
def prod.fst {F G : C ⥤ Type w} : prod F G ⟶ F where
```

As `(F G : C ⥤ Type w)` are variables throughout most of the file, it would be slightly better to add a line like this by the top of the file:
```lean
variable (F G : C ⥤ Type w)
```
Then, you may replace `def prod (F G : C ⥤ Type w) : C ⥤ Type w where` by `def prod : C ⥤ Type w where`. When you need to make parameters implicit or explicit, you may do `variable {F G}` or `variable (F G)`.

Okay I added `F` and `G` as variables. Through the rest of the file I just alternated writing `variable {F G}` and `variable (F G)` whenever necessary (about 8 times), which I'm not sure is good practice. This seems a little excessive, so maybe I misunderstood what you meant.
This seems good to me. (When only one definition needs such change, we could also do `variable {F G} in def ....`, but it is not necessary here.)

In order to mimic the product API naming, I would suggest this name:
```suggestion
def prod.lift {F F₁ F₂ : C ⥤ Type w} (τ₁ : F ⟶ F₁) (τ₂ : F ⟶ F₂) :
```
It would be nice to add equational (simp) lemmas like `prod.lift_fst : prod.lift τ₁ τ₂ ≫ prod.fst = τ₁`. (The `apply` version of these should be obtained by adding the `@[simps]` attribute to `prod.lift`.)
Similarly, this one should be `coprod.desc`.

Similarly, the parentheses are not necessary here and just below:
```suggestion
def coprod.inl {F G : C ⥤ Type w} : F ⟶ coprod F G where
```

This name would be better:
```suggestion
lemma inl_comp_binaryCoproductIso_hom :
```
(Similar names below should be changed accordingly.)

```suggestion
abbrev coprodInl {a : C} (x : F.obj a) : (F ⨿ G).obj a :=
```
And similarly for `coprodInr`. Hopefully, this may ease automation in future uses of this API.
